<TR>
<!-- <TD></TD> -->
<TD VALIGN="top">A sleek, shiny musical beauty product from a slick Spice Girl, Hot is a dazzlingly polished piece of work. With a smooth crew comprising Missy Elliott, Sisqo, Fred Jerkins, Teddy Riley and Jam And Lewis, Mel B's debut album could easily have slithered up its own gloss. Were it not of course for Mel B. "I'm gonna get all soft and smoocheh" she confesses in a rich and ripe Leeds accent at the start of otherwise pristine pop romp Feels So Good and she's starting as she means to go on. Although songs like Tell Me and Pack Your Sh*t deal with the difficult times and bitter memories of her ex-husband, there's also a lot of fun to be had on the album. There are joyous songs of love like Hotter (which neatly nicks the squelchy effects of Stevie Wonder's Superstitious), ABC 123 and the sweet ode to Phoenix-Chi that is Lullaby. At times the record swamps its star and at times her voice seems lost and lacking without three different harmonies to bulk out some songs, but on the whole Hot, being not as cool a record as maybe its production team envisaged, manages to live up to its name.<P><FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica" SIZE="-2" COLOR="#666666"><I>By Esther Sadler</I></FONT>
</TD>
</TR>
